For this problem we have the following coordinates of the center of mass
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{R}_{CM}=\left(2,2,2\right),
\]

\end_inset

which if, we label the positions of the particles as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}_{i}$
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{R}_{CM}=\frac{\sum_{i}m_{i}\mathbf{r}_{i}}{\sum_{i}m_{i}},
\]

\end_inset

then, we can use the masses of the particles ans write the previous equation,
 in terms of its components as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2=\frac{40x_{1}+50x_{2}+60x_{3}}{40+50+60},
\]

\end_inset

and the same for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, let's focus on the equation for the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 component, and let's simplify it as follows 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2=\frac{4x_{1}+5x_{2}+6x_{3}}{15}\implies30=4x_{1}+5x_{2}+6x_{3},
\]

\end_inset

and the same holds for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, if we add another particle, with a mass of 70 but, this
 time we want that the equilibrium position will be in the point 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(0,0,0\right)$
\end_inset

, this is equivalent to say 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=\frac{40x_{1}+50x_{2}+60x_{3}+70x_{4}}{40+50+60+70},
\]

\end_inset

and the same for the components 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

, thus we have simplify the equation as follows 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=\frac{40x_{1}+50x_{2}+60x_{3}+70x_{4}}{40+50+60+70}\implies0=40x_{1}+50x_{2}+60x_{3}+70x_{4},
\]

\end_inset

but we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $30=4x_{1}+5x_{2}+6x_{3}$
\end_inset

, thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=30+70x_{4}\implies x_{4}=-\frac{3}{7},
\]

\end_inset

and the same for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

, therefore, the fourth mass needs to be located at 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(-\frac{30}{7},-\frac{30}{7},-\frac{30}{7}\right).
\]

\end_inset


